1
00:00:05,200 --> 00:00:06,560
...something they had never seen,

2
00:00:06,640 --> 00:00:07,920
which liberated a yellow,

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:09,720
very pungent and acrid vapor.

4
00:00:09,840 --> 00:00:11,320
The actions of the hardline military regime

5
00:00:11,440 --> 00:00:13,960
are the cause of increasing
international concern.

6
00:00:14,240 --> 00:00:15,800
The regime crushes all dissent.

7
00:00:15,920 --> 00:00:17,560
Ethnic groups are being oppressed

8
00:00:17,680 --> 00:00:18,760
in the east of the country,

9
00:00:19,040 --> 00:00:20,600
and foreign journalists are rarely...

10
00:00:20,680 --> 00:00:22,080
...claim tonight

11
00:00:22,200 --> 00:00:23,520
that some form of chemical weapon

12
00:00:23,840 --> 00:00:25,360
has been used in Burma
by military rulers...

13
00:00:25,440 --> 00:00:27,240
...has led to the national uprising.

14
00:00:27,360 --> 00:00:28,840
Thousands took to the streets,

15
00:00:28,960 --> 00:00:30,840
- and thousands were killed
- In Burma,

16
00:00:30,920 --> 00:00:32,600
- by the Burmese military.
- protesting monks have been killed...

17
00:00:32,720 --> 00:00:34,840
some burned alive,
and others drowned.

18
00:00:34,960 --> 00:00:36,880
Foreign journalists
have been shot and killed.

19
00:00:36,960 --> 00:00:38,800
...as thousands of villages
have been destroyed,

20
00:00:38,880 --> 00:00:40,640
rape and torture
are a daily occurrence.

21
00:00:40,760 --> 00:00:42,360
In Burma, there are more landmines

22
00:00:42,440 --> 00:00:43,600
- than anywhere in the world.
- Young men are beaten

23
00:00:43,680 --> 00:00:45,080
and forced into the army,

24
00:00:45,160 --> 00:00:47,040
many as young as 12 years old.

25
00:00:47,120 --> 00:00:48,960
Beheadings and mutilations
are commonplace.

26
00:00:49,080 --> 00:00:50,120
The Karen people,

27
00:00:50,240 --> 00:00:51,560
comprised mostly
of poor Christian farmers,

28
00:00:51,680 --> 00:00:53,240
have been singled out for extermination.

29
00:00:53,520 --> 00:00:55,000
The ruling military government

30
00:00:55,120 --> 00:00:57,720
wants the abundant national resources
on Karen land.

31
00:00:57,840 --> 00:00:59,520
The bloody Burmese military campaign

32
00:00:59,640 --> 00:01:02,240
against the Karen people has been
going on for almost 60 years...

33
00:01:02,360 --> 00:01:04,720
the longest running civil war

34
00:01:04,800 --> 00:01:06,520
in the world.

35
00:02:15,800 --> 00:02:17,680
Hey! Hey!

36
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:10,600
...number one.

37
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:12,560
First snake that you see,

38
00:06:12,640 --> 00:06:14,360
they are Siamese cobra.

39
00:06:14,480 --> 00:06:17,080
Oh, come on, cobra.

40
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:18,600
He is not king cobra

41
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:20,200
and not spitting cobra.

42
00:06:26,040 --> 00:06:27,280
Hey! Hey!

43
00:06:37,040 --> 00:06:39,160
Fuck off, okay?

44
00:06:44,160 --> 00:06:47,120
...still have fang
and still have poison.

45
00:06:48,880 --> 00:06:51,360
He is small, dangerous...
Number one.

46
00:06:52,520 --> 00:06:54,520
King cobra number two.

47
00:06:55,800 --> 00:06:57,040
And now spitting cobra.

48
00:06:57,120 --> 00:06:59,960
He can spit poison to your eye.

49
00:07:02,520 --> 00:07:05,280
One color.

50
00:07:05,360 --> 00:07:07,560
He is very, very dangerous.
Number one in Thailand.

51
00:07:07,680 --> 00:07:10,120
Careful, my friend.

52
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:14,760
Looks like dangerous work.

53
00:07:16,320 --> 00:07:19,160
I'm Michael Burnett.
Do you have some time to talk?

54
00:07:19,280 --> 00:07:21,200
Won't take long.
I promise.

55
00:07:21,280 --> 00:07:23,280
I was told it might be possible
to rent your boat.

56
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:24,440
We'd like to do that.

57
00:07:24,520 --> 00:07:26,160
Is that possible?
We need to get upriver.

58
00:07:26,240 --> 00:07:27,680
Where you going?

59
00:07:27,760 --> 00:07:30,200
Into Burma.

60
00:07:30,280 --> 00:07:31,640
Burma's a war zone.

61
00:07:31,720 --> 00:07:33,960
Well, that's what people call it,

62
00:07:34,080 --> 00:07:36,920
but it's more like genocide than war.

63
00:07:37,240 --> 00:07:38,840
Anyway, this will be my fifth trip in,

64
00:07:38,920 --> 00:07:41,760
so we are aware of all the risks.

65
00:07:44,440 --> 00:07:46,280
I don't go that far north.

66
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:48,320
Let me explain our situation.

67
00:07:48,440 --> 00:07:50,720
Our church is part of
a Pan-Asian ministry

68
00:07:50,840 --> 00:07:52,160
located in Colorado.

69
00:07:52,280 --> 00:07:53,760
We're all volunteers

70
00:07:53,880 --> 00:07:55,200
who, around this time of year,

71
00:07:55,520 --> 00:07:57,400
bring in medical supplies,

72
00:07:57,520 --> 00:07:59,000
medical attention,

73
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:00,280
prayer books, and support

74
00:08:00,400 --> 00:08:02,800
for the Karen tribespeople.

75
00:08:02,880 --> 00:08:04,760
People say you know the river
better than anyone.

76
00:08:04,840 --> 00:08:07,640
- Well, they lied.
- So what I'm asking is

77
00:08:07,720 --> 00:08:08,920
that we compensate you

78
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,480
for a few hours of your time

79
00:08:11,560 --> 00:08:13,400
that will help change people's lives.

80
00:08:16,920 --> 00:08:18,120
Are you bringing in any weapons?

81
00:08:18,240 --> 00:08:19,960
Of course not.

82
00:08:20,040 --> 00:08:21,960
You're not changing anything.

83
00:08:23,040 --> 00:08:25,800
Well...

84
00:08:25,920 --> 00:08:29,000
it's thinking like that that keeps
the world the way it is.

85
00:08:29,120 --> 00:08:30,680
Fuck the world.

86
00:08:33,320 --> 00:08:34,400
- Let's go.
- Why?

87
00:08:34,520 --> 00:08:36,640
He's not interested.
Let's just go.

88
00:08:36,760 --> 00:08:37,880
- Let me try.
- No, Sarah...

89
00:08:37,960 --> 00:08:39,600
Didn't you say it was
the only way up there?

90
00:08:39,680 --> 00:08:41,160
- I know I did.
- Then what do we have to lose?

91
00:08:41,280 --> 00:08:42,720
- I talked to the man...
- Just let me try, Michael.

92
00:08:42,840 --> 00:08:43,800
- Sarah...
- Please.

93
00:08:43,920 --> 00:08:44,880
You...

94
00:08:52,800 --> 00:08:53,920
Hello?

95
00:08:55,200 --> 00:08:57,040
I'm Sarah Miller.

96
00:08:57,120 --> 00:09:00,360
I hope you don't mind me
coming back here.

97
00:09:00,480 --> 00:09:01,880
The man that you
were talking to...

98
00:09:01,960 --> 00:09:03,320
I wasn't talking to anybody.

99
00:09:06,240 --> 00:09:07,400
All right, uh...

100
00:09:07,520 --> 00:09:09,360
the man that was talking
to you asked

101
00:09:09,440 --> 00:09:11,760
if we could hire you
to take us up the river.

102
00:09:11,840 --> 00:09:13,800
You said no. Why?

103
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:15,680
Can't help you out.

104
00:09:17,080 --> 00:09:18,360
Well, if you have good reasons,

105
00:09:18,480 --> 00:09:20,560
would you mind if I heard them?

106
00:09:23,320 --> 00:09:25,720
Go home.

107
00:11:55,040 --> 00:11:56,920
Why'd you come back?

108
00:11:58,400 --> 00:11:59,320
Waiting for you.

109
00:12:03,960 --> 00:12:05,560
I told you before,
I can't help you.

110
00:12:05,880 --> 00:12:07,680
Well, we need to go
and help these people.

111
00:12:07,760 --> 00:12:09,240
We're here to make a difference.

112
00:12:09,320 --> 00:12:11,840
We believe all lives are special.

113
00:12:11,960 --> 00:12:14,160
- Some lives, some no.
- Really?

114
00:12:14,440 --> 00:12:16,000
If everyone thought like you,
nothing would ever change.

115
00:12:16,120 --> 00:12:18,280
- Nothing does change.
- Of course it does.

116
00:12:18,400 --> 00:12:19,400
Nothing stays the same.

117
00:12:19,520 --> 00:12:21,240
Live your life,
'cause you got a good one.

118
00:12:21,360 --> 00:12:22,720
It's what I'm trying to do.

119
00:12:22,840 --> 00:12:24,720
No, what you're trying
to do is change what is.

120
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:26,280
And what is?

121
00:12:28,280 --> 00:12:29,240
Go home.

122
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:33,920
Really. Go home.

123
00:12:58,960 --> 00:13:01,080
Maybe...

124
00:13:01,160 --> 00:13:04,360
maybe you've lost
your faith in people,

125
00:13:04,480 --> 00:13:07,320
but you must still
be faithful to something.

126
00:13:07,440 --> 00:13:09,560
You must still care
about something.

127
00:13:10,760 --> 00:13:14,280
Maybe we can't change what is...

128
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:16,040
but trying to save a life

129
00:13:16,160 --> 00:13:18,240
isn't wasting your life.

130
00:13:18,360 --> 00:13:19,360
Is it?

131
00:13:42,440 --> 00:13:43,840
As bad as these people are,

132
00:13:43,920 --> 00:13:45,240
they will eventually lose.

133
00:13:45,320 --> 00:13:47,560
They can't keep it up
against a united front.

134
00:13:47,680 --> 00:13:49,480
They can't.

135
00:13:49,600 --> 00:13:50,640
I mean, time alone will tell,

136
00:13:50,720 --> 00:13:51,960
but in the meantime,

137
00:13:52,280 --> 00:13:53,680
we just have to help
hold it together.

138
00:13:53,760 --> 00:13:55,560
I mean, just the other day...

139
00:13:55,680 --> 00:13:56,680
Excuse me.

140
00:13:56,800 --> 00:13:58,680
Sarah, where are you going?

141
00:13:58,760 --> 00:14:00,320
To talk to him.

142
00:14:00,440 --> 00:14:02,840
Well, he... He probably
wants his privacy.

143
00:14:02,960 --> 00:14:04,640
Michael, we shouldn't ignore him.

144
00:14:04,760 --> 00:14:06,320
- He's helping us.
- He's been paid.

145
00:14:06,600 --> 00:14:08,920
He didn't take anything.

146
00:14:15,840 --> 00:14:17,720
Thank you again for doing this.

147
00:14:17,800 --> 00:14:18,760
Really.

148
00:14:18,880 --> 00:14:20,600
From all of us.

149
00:14:20,680 --> 00:14:23,520
You know you never
told us your name.

150
00:14:23,600 --> 00:14:24,600
John.

151
00:14:25,800 --> 00:14:27,400
Where you from?

152
00:14:27,520 --> 00:14:29,320
Bowie, Arizona.

153
00:14:29,440 --> 00:14:31,040
Why'd you leave?

154
00:14:31,160 --> 00:14:32,200
I got drafted in 'Nam.

155
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:33,920
And you just stayed?

156
00:14:35,880 --> 00:14:37,080
It's complicated.

157
00:14:38,280 --> 00:14:39,800
You have family back home?

158
00:14:39,920 --> 00:14:42,080
Father maybe. I don't know.

159
00:14:44,560 --> 00:14:45,640
Aren't you curious to see

160
00:14:45,760 --> 00:14:47,480
how things might have
changed back home?

161
00:14:49,840 --> 00:14:51,680
Got to have a reason for that.

162
00:14:56,320 --> 00:14:58,120
Sarah.

163
00:14:58,240 --> 00:14:59,880
Because of you, we're going upriver.

164
00:15:01,480 --> 00:15:02,880
Anytime you want to turn around,

165
00:15:02,960 --> 00:15:04,120
it's done.

166
00:15:06,320 --> 00:15:07,320
Okay.

167
00:15:57,600 --> 00:15:59,040
What is it?
Who are they?

168
00:15:59,120 --> 00:16:00,760
Burmese pirates.

169
00:16:00,880 --> 00:16:02,640
Tell everyone to stay down,
don't make a sound.

170
00:16:04,560 --> 00:16:06,120
- Who are they?
- It's all right.

171
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:07,520
- Just keep...
- Don't talk.

172
00:16:44,360 --> 00:16:46,360
- Any more of them?
- Maybe.

173
00:16:46,480 --> 00:16:48,000
What do you want to do?

174
00:16:48,120 --> 00:16:49,880
We should keep going.
We made a commitment.

175
00:16:49,960 --> 00:16:51,960
I ain't talking to you.

176
00:16:52,040 --> 00:16:53,760
- What do you want to do?
- We're a group here.

177
00:16:53,880 --> 00:16:54,920
If they wanna vote...

178
00:16:57,080 --> 00:16:58,200
Sit down!

179
00:16:58,320 --> 00:16:59,680
If it's money they want,
we'll give them what...

180
00:17:02,480 --> 00:17:04,480
Nobody talks.
Heads down.

181
00:17:13,200 --> 00:17:15,200
Keep your heads down,
and nobody look 'em in the eye,

182
00:17:15,320 --> 00:17:17,480
or they'll kill you.

183
00:19:01,520 --> 00:19:02,680
No!

184
00:19:09,360 --> 00:19:11,040
What did you do?

185
00:19:11,160 --> 00:19:13,240
We came here to help
stop the killing!

186
00:19:13,560 --> 00:19:14,680
Who are you to...

187
00:19:14,800 --> 00:19:16,440
- Who are you?
- Let him go!

188
00:19:16,520 --> 00:19:17,920
They would have
raped her 50 times

189
00:19:18,040 --> 00:19:20,880
and cut your fucking heads off.

190
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:22,320
Who are you?

191
00:19:22,400 --> 00:19:23,840
Who are any of you?

192
00:19:26,040 --> 00:19:27,960
We're going back!

193
00:19:31,920 --> 00:19:32,880
No.

194
00:19:32,960 --> 00:19:35,160
No, we shouldn't go back.

195
00:19:35,280 --> 00:19:36,800
Let go.

196
00:19:36,920 --> 00:19:38,680
What are you doing?

197
00:19:38,800 --> 00:19:40,160
We are so close.

198
00:19:40,480 --> 00:19:43,320
What happened here,
it's horrible.

199
00:19:43,400 --> 00:19:44,920
But the people in there

200
00:19:45,000 --> 00:19:47,120
are being killed like this every day.

201
00:19:47,200 --> 00:19:49,960
Michael, this was your idea.

202
00:19:50,080 --> 00:19:52,520
We made a commitment.

203
00:19:52,640 --> 00:19:55,320
I know you don't believe
in what we're doing,

204
00:19:55,440 --> 00:19:58,360
but it's our life, our choice.

205
00:19:59,960 --> 00:20:02,200
You're not gonna change anything.

206
00:20:04,480 --> 00:20:06,480
Please.

207
00:20:06,560 --> 00:20:08,480
Please, John. Please.

208
00:20:22,240 --> 00:20:23,240
Go sit down.

209
00:20:31,440 --> 00:20:32,400
I'm sorry.

210
00:21:19,480 --> 00:21:20,720
We'll be taking
the overland route

211
00:21:20,800 --> 00:21:22,240
on the way back,

212
00:21:22,320 --> 00:21:24,120
so there's no need
to wait around.

213
00:21:24,200 --> 00:21:27,040
I have to report this.

214
00:21:27,120 --> 00:21:29,160
I know you think
what you did was right,

215
00:21:29,280 --> 00:21:31,120
but taking a life is never right.

216
00:21:47,280 --> 00:21:49,600
I don't know what to say.

217
00:21:49,880 --> 00:21:52,360
Then you shouldn't
say anything, should you?

218
00:21:52,480 --> 00:21:54,200
Good luck.

219
00:23:52,680 --> 00:23:53,640
Hey.

220
00:24:40,880 --> 00:24:43,520
Mm-hmm.
Good, good.

221
00:24:43,640 --> 00:24:44,560
Mm-hmm.

222
00:24:46,720 --> 00:24:47,960
Open.

223
00:24:51,840 --> 00:24:53,080
Yeah, good.

224
00:25:00,400 --> 00:25:02,240
With power, through the spirit

225
00:25:02,360 --> 00:25:03,720
in your inner being.

226
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:10,360
So Christ may dwell
in your hearts with faith.

227
00:25:14,640 --> 00:25:18,520
And I pray...

228
00:25:18,600 --> 00:25:21,000
you may have power together...

229
00:25:22,920 --> 00:25:25,680
Let me see if I can fix
this little problem, okay?

230
00:25:27,560 --> 00:25:28,640
Okay.

231
00:25:39,440 --> 00:25:41,120
Hey, you.

232
00:25:41,240 --> 00:25:43,400
Hand me one of those bandages?

233
00:25:43,520 --> 00:25:45,760
Okay.

234
00:25:45,880 --> 00:25:46,960
Thank you.

235
00:25:47,040 --> 00:25:48,360
Okay.

236
00:26:05,440 --> 00:26:07,000
- Get out of here!
- What about them?

237
00:26:07,120 --> 00:26:08,280
Go on! Take them!

238
00:26:26,760 --> 00:26:27,720
No!

239
00:29:33,080 --> 00:29:36,000
Company leader calling Raven.
Come on, Raven.

240
00:29:37,560 --> 00:29:38,480
What am I?

241
00:29:38,600 --> 00:29:39,960
You made me this way.

242
00:29:40,040 --> 00:29:41,400
A full-blooded combat soldier.

243
00:29:41,480 --> 00:29:42,880
You just don't turn it off.

244
00:29:43,000 --> 00:29:44,280
Talk to me, Johnny.

245
00:29:44,360 --> 00:29:45,840
You just don't turn it off!

246
00:29:45,920 --> 00:29:47,520
- It's over!
- Nothing is over!

247
00:29:49,960 --> 00:29:52,480
When are you gonna
come full circle?

248
00:29:52,600 --> 00:29:54,320
- I know the reasons you're here, John.
- No!

249
00:29:55,440 --> 00:29:56,600
Aren't you curious to see

250
00:29:56,680 --> 00:29:57,720
how things might have
changed back home?

251
00:30:00,120 --> 00:30:02,040
You've done enough damage.

252
00:30:02,160 --> 00:30:04,120
You're always gonna be
tearing away at yourself

253
00:30:04,200 --> 00:30:06,000
until you come to terms
with what you are.

254
00:30:06,080 --> 00:30:07,320
Until you come full circle.

255
00:30:07,680 --> 00:30:09,240
So you're just gonna
stay here forever?

256
00:30:09,320 --> 00:30:12,560
- John!
- I wanna go home!

257
00:30:12,640 --> 00:30:14,800
John Rambo!

258
00:30:14,880 --> 00:30:16,920
John?

259
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:18,520
John Rambo?

260
00:30:30,280 --> 00:30:32,000
My name is Arthur Marsh...

261
00:30:33,200 --> 00:30:36,440
pastor of the Christ Church
in Colorado.

262
00:30:36,560 --> 00:30:38,360
I need to talk with you.

263
00:30:38,480 --> 00:30:42,480
It's very important. I wouldn't
come here like this if it wasn't.

264
00:30:45,120 --> 00:30:47,600
The morning of the day
the group left,

265
00:30:47,880 --> 00:30:50,040
Michael Burnett notified me

266
00:30:50,160 --> 00:30:51,800
that they were traveling
from this location.

267
00:30:55,840 --> 00:30:56,760
What happened?

268
00:30:56,880 --> 00:30:58,720
No one knows exactly.

269
00:30:58,800 --> 00:31:00,760
They were supposed
to return 10 days ago,

270
00:31:00,880 --> 00:31:02,040
but they never came back.

271
00:31:02,320 --> 00:31:05,200
I requested help from the embassy,
but they can't help,

272
00:31:05,320 --> 00:31:08,440
not in Burma, and not in time.

273
00:31:08,520 --> 00:31:09,480
How do you know they're alive?

274
00:31:09,600 --> 00:31:11,000
Because we've been in contact

275
